  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, the activity of money laundering is strictly prohibited by law in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (commonly referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal by disguising its true source. This activity is typically associated with criminal enterprises and is used to legitimize funds obtained through illegal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and other forms of organized crime.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is a federal crime under the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). The act prohibits knowingly engaging in financial transactions involving the proceeds of unlawful activities for the purpose of concealing the nature, source, or ownership of the proceeds or to avoid a transaction reporting requirement under state or federal law.\n\nSimilarly, in the European Union, money laundering is addressed by the Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD), which require member states to implement measures to prevent the financial system from being used for money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nInternational cooperation in the fight against money laundering is also a key component of the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nPenalties for engaging in money laundering activities can be severe and may include significant fines and imprisonment. Additionally, financial institutions and other regulated entities are required to establish anti-money laundering (AML) programs to detect and report suspicious activities to the authorities.",
